name: 1-fluoro-2-nitrobenzene
Reason: To predict the melting point of 1-fluoro-2-nitrobenzene, we will consider the melting point of benzene as the basic unit and the effects of the two substituents, fluorine and the nitro group. Benzene has a melting point of 5.5°C. A fluorine atom typically causes a slight increase in the melting point due to its inductive effect and ability to participate in dipole-dipole interactions, so let's estimate this contribution to be around +20°C. The nitro group is a strong electron-withdrawing group and can form strong intermolecular bonds such as hydrogen bonds, which can considerably raise the melting point. We will estimate this effect to be around +50°C. However, these are wide estimations, and thus the actual effect might be slightly different, considering the specific positioning of the groups on the benzene ring influencing the overall crystal packing.
